7:44:44 AM [express] POST /api/mealplan 200 in 25841ms :: {"profile_summary":"20-year-old moderately active male (170 cm, 65 kg, BMI 22.5) with no medical issues or allergies, seeking to reduce inflammation and balance a predominantly Vata constitution using Indian cuisine within a moderate budget and up to 1 hour cooking time.","hydration":"Aim for about 2.3â€“2.5 liters of fluids per day, mainly as warm water or herbal infusions; keep a thermos of warm water or ginger-tulsi tea at your desk and sip regularly instead of drinking large amounts at once.","why_this_works":"The day emphasizes warm, moist, lightly spiced meals with healthy fats and good-quality protein to ground Vata and reduce systemic inflammation. Anti-inflammatory ingredients like turmeric, ginger, garlic, methi, coriander, amla, and colorful vegetables are used repeatedly, along with low-to-moderate glycemic whole grains and legumes for stable energy. Ghee, nuts, and seeds provide Vata-pacifying unctuousness while avoiding excessive dryness, cold foods, and stimulants that can aggravate Vata.","meals":{"breakfast":{"dish_name":"Moong Dal Vegetable Khichdi with Ghee and Amla-Coriander Chutney","ingredients":["Split yellow moong dal (soaked) â€“ 40 g","Short-grain rice â€“ 40 g","Carrot, diced â€“ 30 g","Bottle gourd (lauki), diced â€“ 40 g","Green peas â€“ 20 g","Fresh ginger, grated â€“ 5 g","Turmeric powder â€“ 1/4 tsp","Cumin seeds â€“ 1/2 tsp","Black pepper, freshly ground â€“ 1/4 tsp","Ghee â€“ 10 g (about 2 tsp)","Salt â€“ to taste","Water â€“ ~350â€“400 ml","For chutney: fresh amla â€“ 20 g, fresh coriander leaves â€“ 10 g, garlic â€“ 1 clove, black pepper â€“ a pinch, rock salt â€“ to taste, 1â€“2 tsp warm water"],"portion":"1 medium bowl khichdi (~350 g) + 2 tbsp chutney (~30 g)","macros":{"protein":"14 g","carbs":"60 g","fat":"11 g","calories":"420 kcal"},"why":"Warm, soft khichdi is classic for calming Vata, easy to digest, and the combination of rice and moong provides complete protein with low inflammatory load. Ghee, turmeric, ginger, black pepper, and amla-coriander chutney add anti-inflammatory and antioxidant benefits while keeping the meal unctuous and grounding.","substitutions":["Replace rice with quinoa (same quantity) if you prefer a higher-protein, slightly nuttier option while keeping it Vata-friendly by cooking very soft.","Swap bottle gourd with pumpkin or sweet potato in the same amount if those are more easily available."]},"morning_snack":{"dish_name":"Warm Spiced Pomegranate-Orange Infused Water with Soaked Walnuts","ingredients":["Pomegranate arils â€“ 40 g (~1/4 cup)","Orange segments â€“ 40 g (~1/4 cup)","Warm water â€“ 200 ml","Clove â€“ 1 piece","Black pepper, freshly crushed â€“ a pinch","Fresh ginger slice â€“ 3â€“4 g","Walnuts, soaked overnight â€“ 15 g (about 3 halves)"],"portion":"1 mug infused warm drink (~250 ml including fruit) + 3 soaked walnut halves (~15 g)","macros":{"protein":"3 g","carbs":"16 g","fat":"7 g","calories":"140 kcal"},"why":"Pomegranate and orange provide vitamin C and polyphenols that help reduce inflammation, while warming spices and serving the drink warm make it more suitable for Vata. Soaked walnuts add omega-3 fats for anti-inflammatory support and healthy unctuousness without being too heavy.","substitutions":["If fresh pomegranate is unavailable, use 60 ml unsweetened pomegranate juice and top up with warm water.","Replace walnuts with 8â€“10 soaked almonds if walnuts are not available, keeping the portion similar."]},"lunch":{"dish_name":"Jeera Rice with Methi-Toor Dal Tadka and Stir-Fried Drumstick-Carrot Subzi","ingredients":["For jeera rice: basmati rice â€“ 70 g, ghee â€“ 5 g (1 tsp), cumin seeds â€“ 1/2 tsp, salt â€“ to taste, water â€“ ~200 ml","For methi-toor dal: toor dal (arhar) â€“ 45 g (soaked), fresh methi leaves chopped â€“ 25 g, tomato â€“ 30 g, onion â€“ 20 g, garlic â€“ 2 cloves, ginger â€“ 5 g, turmeric powder â€“ 1/4 tsp, coriander powder â€“ 1/2 tsp, mustard seeds â€“ 1/4 tsp, curry leaves â€“ 4â€“5, dried red chilli â€“ 1 small (optional, mild), ghee or mustard oil â€“ 7 g (~1.5 tsp), salt â€“ to taste, water â€“ ~250 ml","For drumstick-carrot subzi: drumstick (moringa pods), cut â€“ 60 g, carrot â€“ 40 g, onion â€“ 20 g, mustard seeds â€“ 1/4 tsp, curry leaves â€“ 4â€“5, turmeric â€“ a pinch, black pepper â€“ a pinch, mustard oil â€“ 5 g (1 tsp), salt â€“ to taste, water â€“ as needed for light steaming","Fresh coriander leaves â€“ 5 g for garnish"],"portion":"Jeera rice 1 medium plate (~180 g cooked), methi-toor dal ~1.5 katori (~200 g), drumstick-carrot subzi ~1 katori (~120 g)","macros":{"protein":"23 g","carbs":"82 g","fat":"18 g","calories":"640 kcal"},"why":"This lunch combines easily digestible rice with protein-rich toor dal and anti-inflammatory methi, ginger, garlic, turmeric, and curry leaves, all cooked in ghee/mustard oil to suit Vata. Drumstick and carrot add fiber and phytonutrients that support inflammation control while the warm, mildly spiced, oily nature of the meal keeps Vata grounded.","substitutions":["Replace toor dal with masoor dal in the same quantity if that cooks faster or is more available.","If drumstick is not available, use okra (bhindi) or bottle gourd with similar spices and cooking style."]},"evening_snack":{"dish_name":"Masala Vegetable Oats Upma with Tulsi-Ginger Herbal Tea","ingredients":["Rolled oats â€“ 35 g","Carrot, finely chopped â€“ 20 g","Peas â€“ 15 g","Onion, finely chopped â€“ 15 g","Fresh curry leaves â€“ 4â€“5","Mustard seeds â€“ 1/4 tsp","Grated ginger â€“ 3 g","Turmeric â€“ a pinch","Black pepper â€“ a pinch","Ghee or olive oil â€“ 5 g (1 tsp)","Water â€“ ~150â€“180 ml","Salt â€“ to taste","Fresh coriander leaves â€“ 5 g","For tea: fresh tulsi leaves â€“ 6â€“8, ginger slice â€“ 3 g, clove â€“ 1, warm water â€“ 200 ml"],"portion":"1 small bowl oats upma (~180 g) + 1 cup tulsi-ginger tea (~200 ml)","macros":{"protein":"7 g","carbs":"30 g","fat":"6 g","calories":"220 kcal"},"why":"Light but warm and savory oats upma with vegetables provides steady energy and fiber without spiking blood sugar, while ghee and spices keep it Vata-pacifying. Tulsi-ginger tea adds additional anti-inflammatory and immune-supportive benefits and is served warm to avoid Vata aggravation from cold drinks.","substitutions":["Replace oats with finely broken wheat (dalia) if preferred, cooking slightly longer with extra water.","Use olive oil instead of ghee if you want a plant-based fat while still keeping it warm and unctuous."]},"dinner":{"dish_name":"Soft Phulka Roti with Moong-Masoor Dal Tadka and Pumpkin-Okra Coconut-Free Curry","ingredients":["For phulka: whole wheat atta â€“ 60 g, warm water â€“ as needed, pinch of salt (optional), ghee for brushing â€“ 5 g (1 tsp)","For moong-masoor dal: split yellow moong dal â€“ 25 g, split red masoor dal â€“ 25 g (both soaked), onion â€“ 25 g, tomato â€“ 30 g, garlic â€“ 2 cloves, ginger â€“ 5 g, turmeric â€“ 1/4 tsp, cumin seeds â€“ 1/2 tsp, black pepper â€“ 1/4 tsp, coriander powder â€“ 1/2 tsp, ghee â€“ 7 g (~1.5 tsp), salt â€“ to taste, water â€“ ~250 ml, fresh coriander â€“ 5 g","For pumpkin-okra curry: pumpkin cubes â€“ 60 g, okra (bhindi) â€“ 60 g, onion â€“ 20 g, mustard seeds â€“ 1/4 tsp, curry leaves â€“ 4â€“5, turmeric â€“ a pinch, coriander powder â€“ 1/4 tsp, black pepper â€“ a pinch, mustard oil â€“ 5 g (1 tsp), salt â€“ to taste, water â€“ splash for light gravy"],"portion":"2 soft phulkas (~90 g cooked) with ghee, dal ~1.5 katori (~200 g), pumpkin-okra curry ~1 katori (~120 g)","macros":{"protein":"22 g","carbs":"78 g","fat":"18 g","calories":"620 kcal"},"why":"Dinner is warm, light-to-moderate, and easy to digest, which is ideal for Vata in the evening, with mixed lentils providing complete protein and steady energy. Pumpkin and okra are naturally Vata-friendly vegetables, and the use of ghee/mustard oil plus gentle spices like turmeric, ginger, garlic, and black pepper supports anti-inflammatory pathways without overheating Pitta.","substitutions":["Replace whole wheat phulka with jowar or bajra roti if you want to rotate grains; ensure they are brushed with a little ghee to keep them soft for Vata.","If okra is not available, use bottle gourd or carrot with pumpkin in the same curry base."]}}}
